Title:
COMouflage: Stealthy DLL Surrogate Injection for Process Tree Evasion

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This write-up describes “COMouflage,” a Windows code-execution/injection technique that abuses COM’s DLL Surrogate feature to run an attacker-controlled DLL inside `dllhost.exe`.  
- The attacker creates per-user COM registration under `HKCU\Software\Classes\AppID\{GUID}` and `HKCU\Software\Classes\CLSID\{GUID}`, avoiding admin rights.  
- Setting `AppID\DllSurrogate` to an empty string forces Windows to use the default surrogate host (`dllhost.exe`), and `CLSID\...\InprocServer32` points to the malicious DLL path.  
- Triggering `CoCreateInstance` with `CLSCTX_LOCAL_SERVER` causes COM SCM to spawn the surrogate via COM services (`svchost.exe` → `dllhost.exe`), making the attacker process disappear from the visible process lineage.  
- It’s primarily useful for red teams and malware developers focused on parent/process-tree evasion and “living off the land” execution via legitimate COM plumbing.  
- The post also includes a C++ PoC and a basic YARA rule aimed at detecting the registry/API patterns associated with this technique.

Technical Focus:
- COM registration hijacking via HKCU (`Software\Classes\AppID` / `Software\Classes\CLSID`)
- DLL Surrogate mechanism (`DllSurrogate` → default `dllhost.exe`)
- COM activation and instantiation (`CoInitializeEx`, `CoCreateInstance`, `CLSCTX_LOCAL_SERVER`)
- Process tree / parent masquerading (`svchost.exe` spawning `dllhost.exe`)
- WinAPI registry manipulation (`RegCreateKeyExW`, `RegSetValueExW`)
- Detection ideas (static indicators + YARA)

Use Cases:
- Execute payload DLLs inside `dllhost.exe` without classic remote-thread injection
- Evade simplistic EDR detections relying on suspicious parent-child process chains
- User-level (non-admin) COM-based execution and potential persistence via registry
- Build detections for anomalous per-user COM surrogate registrations and activations

Keywords:
COM, DllSurrogate, dllhost.exe, svchost.exe, COM SCM, CoCreateInstance, CLSCTX_LOCAL_SERVER, CLSID, AppID, HKCU, Software\Classes, InprocServer32, ThreadingModel, RegCreateKeyExW, RegSetValueExW, process tree evasion, parent PID masquerading, COM hijacking, T1546.015, YARA